w states punish violations in other countries, when shaming leads to an improvement in human rights conditions, and when it backfires.Drawing on a wide range of evidence—from large-scale cross-national data to original survey experiments and detailed case studies—Rochelle Terman shows how human rights shaming is a deeply political process, one that operates in and through strategic relationships. Arguing that preexisting geopolitical relationships condition both the causes and consequences of shaming in world politics, she shows how adversaries are quick to condemn human rights abuses but often provoke a counterproductive response while friends and allies are the most effective shamers but can be reluctant to impose meaningful sanctions.Upending conventional wisdom on the role of norms in world affairs, The Geopolitics of Shaming demonstrates that politicization is integral to—not a corruption of—the success of the global human rights project.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman rights advocacyxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman rightsxInternational cooperation. 0aInternational relationsxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aTransnational advocacy.  aUPR.  aUnited Nations.  aUniversal Periodic Review.  adomestic politics.  ahuman rights abusers.  ahuman rights enforcement.  ahuman rights violations.  ahuman rights.  ainternational human rights.  ainternational monitoring.  ainternational norms.  ainternational organizations.  ainternational pressure.  ainternational relations.  ainternational shaming.  amoral persuasion.  anaming and shaming.  apolicymaking.  apolitical science.  apolitical theory.  apolitics.  apublic opinion.  apunishment strategy.  asexuality rights.  ashamers.  asocial sanctions.  astate behavior.  astra